data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new **span conversions** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees **cannot represent Span-based method calls**, so this throws at runtime when compiled/interpreted.

## Fix options

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches force the compiler to pick the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees can represent. The same issue affects `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` there too.
